title: For Sale:  Ruger Factory Engraved Single-Six (1957)
postcontent: Ruger Factory Engraved Single-Six, serial number 74393. Manufactured November 1957 and shipped in February 1958. The engraving is the “Ruger Standard Pattern”, with an engraved loading gate and varnished walnut grip panels. The gun is about 98%-99% overall condition and the cylinder frame has turned a pleasing plumb color. The fitted case is very nice inside and outside except two corners at the back side of the lid are damaged from a mouse chewing on them while in storage. There were 238 Single-Sixes engraved in four distinctly different patterns for Ruger by Charles H. Jerred. About half of them were engraved in this pattern and minor sub-variants are found within the group. We will include a copy of the invoice from Ruger to the engraver, copy of the invoice from the engraver to Ruger for the work. title: For Sale:  M1 Garand IHC
postcontent: Garand probably built in the latter part of 1954, very late model Garand with all of the improvements of this type. IHC manufactured approximately 337,623 of the total 5,468,772 rifles produced since 1936, if you believe Scott Duff's research into the matter. This one bears a date of the 307th day of 1954 from the Julian date stamped into the inside of the stock when the wood was tooled out by the Frank Overton Company. Line Materials made the barrel. They set out to produce among the finest barrels ever put on a Garand. This is arguably the scarcest Garand to be had and this one is just about as-issued in 1954, save probably the handguards have almost assuredly been replaced at some point. The MW is a 2.8 approximately and the TE is a 4 and the bore is shiney from one end to the other. Obviously this particular rifle never saw a hostile environment in its 61 year history.

title: For Sale:  KEL TEC KSG SHOTGUN BULLPUP 12GA BLACK
location: 10623 N MAY AVE, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma
postcontent: The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3". This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of various accessories. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil. The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.
